\fs42 \cf5 \strokec5 CHICAGO (Reuters) - Jim Sinegal built a retail empire with a simple credo: don\'92t overcharge for anything, not even hot dogs.\
Over 28 years, Sinegal turned Costco Wholesale Corp\'a0COST.O\'a0from one warehouse into a $78 billion global chain, selling everything from gasoline to diapers and big-screen TVs.\
He\'92s now handing the CEO reins to another company veteran, Craig Jelinek, who would do well to heed Sinegal\'92s philosophy.\
Costco keeps expenses low, everywhere from its Issaquah, Washington headquarters to stores, where shoppers who pay annual membership fees of up to $100 carry purchases out in their own bags or reused cardboard boxes.\
Members paid more than $6 billion to fill up at Costco\'92s gas stations during fiscal 2010, but it is the $1.50 hot-dog-and-fountain-drink combo sold inside the food courts that is most emblematic of Sinegal\'92s business doctrine.\
The price of that combo has been the same since Costco started selling hot dogs from a cart in 1985. In 2010, it sold more than $140 million worth worldwide.\
\'93That $1.50 hot dog and drink makes them prove, every day, their value proposition,\'94 said Patty Edwards, chief investment officer at Trutina Financial, who lives in Costco\'92s hometown.\
\'93Anything in the store, the top margin it can have is 14 percent,\'94 said Edwards. The only exception is products under Costco\'92s own brand, Kirkland Signature, whose margins are allowed to go a notch higher to 15 percent.\
Sinegal, who started as a supermarket bagger, opened the first Costco warehouse in Seattle in 1983 with co-founder Jeff Brotman. Ten years later, Costco merged with The Price Company, known as the initiator of the warehouse club concept.
